    overview: `The Landmark Citizen App is the official payment and engagement platform for Landmark Village — a 9.4-acre mixed-use beachfront development on Victoria Island, Lagos, housing event venues, restaurants, a beach club, retail, and office spaces. The app eliminates cash across the entire ecosystem, replacing it with a digital wallet, loyalty points, and transaction history.

I led end-to-end product design as UI/UX Executive at Landmark Africa Group, working directly with the product manager, engineering team, and facility operations stakeholders. This was a 0→1 initiative — no prior digital product existed for the Landmark community.`,

    challenge: `The core design challenge was layered:

• Multiple user types with different needs — residents, event-goers, restaurant diners, beach visitors, and corporate tenants all needed different entry points into the same payment system.

• Trust barrier — getting users to abandon cash in favour of a digital wallet required the onboarding to communicate security and value immediately. Early user interviews revealed that people associated "cashless" with "losing control of spending."

• Operational complexity — the app had to integrate with point-of-sale systems across 15+ vendors, each with different transaction patterns, while giving the Landmark management team visibility into ecosystem-wide analytics.

• Low digital literacy variance — the user base ranged from tech-savvy young professionals to older residents unfamiliar with mobile wallets.`,

    pullQuote: `The hardest screens weren't the complex ones. They were the simple confirmation dialogs where people decided whether to commit real money to a new system.`,

    approach: [
      'Conducted stakeholder interviews with 8 facility managers, 12 vendors, and 20+ residents to map the full transaction journey from entry to exit across the ecosystem',
      'Created user personas for 4 primary segments: resident, event attendee, casual visitor, corporate tenant — each with distinct frequency, spend patterns, and feature priorities',
      'Designed a progressive onboarding flow that front-loaded wallet setup with a first-deposit incentive, reducing the trust barrier identified in research',
      'Built an information architecture that prioritised the 3 daily-use actions (pay, check balance, view history) as persistent shortcuts, pushing less frequent features into contextual menus',
      'Developed a component-based design system (48 components, 12 patterns) intended for handoff to Landmark\'s in-house team for long-term extension without external design dependency',
      'Ran 3 rounds of prototype testing across different user cohorts — iterated the payment confirmation flow twice after testing revealed hesitation at the final tap',
      'Designed a cashback and rewards layer that surfaced earned points contextually at point-of-purchase, increasing perceived value without adding cognitive load',
    ],

    outcome: `The app launched on both iOS and Android as the official Landmark Citizen platform. It serves as the primary payment interface across the ecosystem, replacing cash transactions at all participating vendors.

Successfully deployed across 15+ vendor touchpoints. Onboarding completion rate exceeded internal targets after progressive disclosure redesign. The cashback and rewards system drove repeat wallet top-ups, establishing a retention loop. Component system was adopted by Landmark\'s in-house team for ongoing feature development, validating the handoff strategy. Maintenance reporting time reduced significantly — in-app issue submission replaced paper forms and fragmented WhatsApp groups.

The design system I built continues to serve as the foundation for all Landmark digital products.`,

    reception: `Adopted as Landmark's primary digital product foundation — my component system is now the reference architecture for every subsequent Landmark app.`,

    reflection: `This project taught me the difference between designing a payment app and designing trust. Every animation timing, every copy choice on the payment confirmation screen, every positioning of the balance display was a trust decision, not a layout decision.

If I were to revisit this project, I\'d push for deeper analytics integration from day one. We shipped tracking late, which meant the first 8 weeks of usage data was sparse.`,

    link: null,
  },

