    overview: `We Are Wear is a fashion marketplace connecting African designers and independent brands with style-conscious shoppers. Unlike conventional e-commerce apps that lead with search and categories, the founder\'s vision was a discovery-first experience — closer to how people browse a curated store than how they search a catalogue.

I joined as the sole product designer, responsible for the complete mobile app experience from onboarding through purchase.`,

    challenge: `The central tension was between discovery and conversion:

• Discovery-first browsing feels good but historically converts poorly — users enjoy scrolling but don\'t add to cart. The design needed to balance inspiration with clear purchase paths.

• Independent African brands are often unfamiliar to shoppers outside their region. Each product card needed to tell a brand story quickly, not just show a price tag.

• Sizing and fit anxiety is the #1 barrier to fashion e-commerce conversion. Without the ability to try on, the product detail page had to carry extra weight in building purchase confidence.

• The founder had strong aesthetic opinions. Translating a brand-owner\'s taste into a functional interface without compromising usability required constant negotiation.`,

    pullQuote: `Fashion is one of the few categories where less information converts better than more. Finding the right amount per screen was the real design work.`,

    approach: [
      'Ran a competitive audit across 12 fashion apps (SSENSE, The RealReal, Jumia, Kisua) to identify where discovery UX succeeds and where it leaks',
      'Designed a dual-mode home feed: curated editorial stories (brand spotlights, style guides) alternating with product grids — browsing feels editorial but always surfaces buyable items',
      'Created product cards that show brand origin, designer name, and a short style note alongside the image and price — giving unfamiliar brands context before the user taps',
      'Designed a "save to closet" mechanic as an intermediate commitment step between browsing and buying, reducing the pressure of the add-to-cart moment',
      'Built detailed size guide components per brand (African sizing standards vary significantly) with a fit-preference questionnaire that personalises recommendations',
      'Prototyped the full checkout flow in Figma with 5 usability test sessions — caught and fixed a critical drop-off at the shipping address step where users expected auto-fill',
    ],

    outcome: `Delivered a complete design system and 60+ screens covering onboarding, discovery feed, product detail, closet/wishlist, checkout, and order tracking. The design was handed off to the engineering team for development.

The discovery feed structure was validated in user testing — participants spent significantly more time browsing compared to a conventional grid-only prototype. The "save to closet" mechanic showed early signal of reducing the browse-to-exit pattern common in fashion apps. Size guide components received strong positive feedback from both the founder and test participants. The design system enabled the single engineer to build consistently without constant design oversight during implementation.`,

    reception: `The founder kept one design decision we initially debated for 3 weeks — the "save to closet" step — because users in testing kept asking for it unprompted.`,

    reflection: `This project sharpened my ability to design for ambiguity. Working with a founder who had strong visual taste was a lesson in separating personal preference from user need. I learned to prototype both directions and let test data settle disagreements.`,

